{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019H4kfgWkcNn5RvcPPaqarz","type":"tool_result","content":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |\n    SPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\n    Date: 2026-06-25\n    Auditor: Automated read-only inspection\n    Scope: RBAC, resource limits, image provenance, job security context, network policy\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 1 — PASSED CONTROLS (correctly configured)\n    ================================================================\n\n    [PASS] Dedicated ServiceAccount\n      A dedicated ServiceAccount 'spark-pi' exists and all workloads\n      (spark-master deployment, spark-worker deployment, spark-pi job)\n      use it explicitly via serviceAccountName: spark-pi. The 'default'\n      ServiceAccount is not used by any workload.\n\n    [PASS] Namespace-scoped RBAC (no ClusterRole)\n      Role 'spark-pi-role' and RoleBinding 'spark-pi-role-binding' are\n      namespace-scoped to spark-pi. No ClusterRole or ClusterRoleBinding\n      grants are present, limiting blast radius to this namespace.\n\n    [PASS] Resource requests and limits set on all containers\n      Every container (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) declares:\n        requests: cpu=200m, memory=512Mi\n        limits:   cpu=500m, memory=1Gi\n      No container runs without a resource budget.\n\n    [PASS] Image tag pinned (not 'latest')\n      All three workloads use apache/spark:3.5.3 — a specific version\n      tag rather than the mutable ':latest' tag.\n\n    [PASS] Job restart policy appropriate for batch\n      The spark-pi Job sets restartPolicy: Never and backoffLimit: 0,\n      ensuring failed pods are not restarted silently, which aids\n      auditability for batch workloads.\n\n    [PASS] Job completed successfully\n      spark-pi Job status: Complete (1 succeeded pod). Duration ~2 min\n      (started 13:46:30Z, completed 13:48:34Z).\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 2 — FAILED / GAP CONTROLS\n    ================================================================\n\n    [FAIL] No securityContext on any pod or container\n      All three pod specs (spark-master deployment, spark-worker\n      deployment, spark-pi job) have securityContext: {} at both the\n      pod and container level. Specific missing hardening:\n        - runAsNonRoot: true  (containers may run as root/UID 0)\n        - runAsUser: <non-zero UID>\n        - allowPrivilegeEscalation: false\n        - readOnlyRootFilesystem: true\n        - capabilities.drop: [ALL]\n        - seccompProfile (RuntimeDefault or Localhost)\n      Risk: containers could run as root and escalate privileges.\n\n    [FAIL] No NetworkPolicy in namespace\n      kubectl get networkpolicy returned no resources. All pods can\n      communicate freely with every other pod/service in the cluster\n      and have unrestricted egress. Network segmentation is absent.\n      Risk: lateral movement is unrestricted if any pod is compromised.\n\n    [FAIL] Image not pinned by digest\n      Image reference is apache/spark:3.5.3 (mutable tag). Tags can be\n      reassigned on the registry; a supply-chain compromise could\n      substitute a malicious image layer while the tag remains the same.\n      Recommended: pin by SHA-256 digest, e.g.\n        apache/spark@sha256:<digest>\n\n    [FAIL] RBAC role overly permissive\n      spark-pi-role grants create/get/list/watch/delete/update/patch on:\n        pods, services, configmaps, persistentvolumeclaims\n      The SparkPi workload runs with --master local[2] (no distributed\n      workers started by the driver) and does not require PVC access or\n      write access to configmaps. Excess verbs and resource types violate\n      the principle of least privilege.\n      Specific concerns:\n        - 'delete' on pods allows arbitrary pod deletion in the namespace\n        - 'update/patch' on configmaps allows configuration tampering\n        - 'create/delete/update/patch' on PVCs is unused and unnecessary\n\n    [FAIL] imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent on all workloads\n      All three pod specs set imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent. Combined\n      with a mutable image tag (see above), this means a node that has\n      already pulled the image will never re-validate it against the\n      registry, making tag-reassignment attacks persistent on cached nodes.\n      Recommended: use Always with digest pinning, or Always with a\n      registry admission policy.\n\n    [FAIL] No namespace-level ResourceQuota\n      There is no ResourceQuota object in the spark-pi namespace. While\n      individual containers have per-container limits, a ResourceQuota\n      would cap total CPU/memory/object-count consumption for the entire\n      namespace, preventing a misconfigured or malicious workload from\n      exhausting cluster-wide resources.\n\n    [FAIL] automountServiceAccountToken not disabled on 'default' ServiceAccount\n      The 'default' ServiceAccount exists (Kubernetes-managed) with no\n      automountServiceAccountToken: false setting. Any pod inadvertently\n      created without an explicit serviceAccountName would auto-mount\n      a token granting API server access. Recommended: set\n      automountServiceAccountToken: false on the default SA.\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 3 — SUMMARY\n    ================================================================\n\n    Passed:  6 controls\n    Failed:  7 controls\n\n    Priority remediation order (highest risk first):\n      1. Add securityContext to all pod/container specs (prevent root execution)\n      2. Add NetworkPolicy to restrict ingress/egress\n      3. Pin images by SHA-256 digest and set imagePullPolicy: Always\n      4. Narrow spark-pi-role to minimum required verbs and resources\n      5. Add namespace ResourceQuota\n      6. Disable automountServiceAccountToken on 'default' ServiceAccount\n\n    NOTE: No changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\n    All findings are based on read-only inspection of live objects.\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-25T13:50:04Z\"\n  name: config-audit\n  namespace: spark-pi\n  resourceVersion: \"1101589\"\n  uid: ddf9f1d4-f1d8-44f1-8ba9-dab8d4d42095","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"09d1cbde-84a9-4ef3-9c55-9514ca301d9c","uuid":"24132b95-736d-4692-a676-106859f9ad92","timestamp":"2026-06-25T13:50:45.739Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |\n    SPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\n    Date: 2026-06-25\n    Auditor: Automated read-only inspection\n    Scope: RBAC, resource limits, image provenance, job security context, network policy\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 1 — PASSED CONTROLS (correctly configured)\n    ================================================================\n\n    [PASS] Dedicated ServiceAccount\n      A dedicated ServiceAccount 'spark-pi' exists and all workloads\n      (spark-master deployment, spark-worker deployment, spark-pi job)\n      use it explicitly via serviceAccountName: spark-pi. The 'default'\n      ServiceAccount is not used by any workload.\n\n    [PASS] Namespace-scoped RBAC (no ClusterRole)\n      Role 'spark-pi-role' and RoleBinding 'spark-pi-role-binding' are\n      namespace-scoped to spark-pi. No ClusterRole or ClusterRoleBinding\n      grants are present, limiting blast radius to this namespace.\n\n    [PASS] Resource requests and limits set on all containers\n      Every container (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) declares:\n        requests: cpu=200m, memory=512Mi\n        limits:   cpu=500m, memory=1Gi\n      No container runs without a resource budget.\n\n    [PASS] Image tag pinned (not 'latest')\n      All three workloads use apache/spark:3.5.3 — a specific version\n      tag rather than 